      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Software used for CFD simulation must be under version control, have documented test suite results, and operate under a quality management system consistent with MRL 5 requirements.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2023 R1) is operated under an ISO 9001-compliant QMS. Version control is enforced via Git with tagged releases. Automated regression test suite covers 98% of solver modules relevant to incompressible turbulent flow. All simulation scripts are archived with checksums. SQA level 3 is fully satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification must demonstrate that the numerical implementation correctly solves the governing equations, using manufactured solutions or equivalent rigorous approaches for the relevant flow physics.",
      "rationale": "The method of manufactured solutions (MMS) was applied to the incompressible Navier-Stokes solver with the k-omega SST turbulence model. Observed convergence rates match theoretical rates (second-order spatial, first-order temporal). Code verification is complete and documented in the solver validation report VR-CFD-2024-003. Level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Discretization error must be quantified using Richardson extrapolation or equivalent, with GCI reported for all quantities of interest across at least three systematically refined meshes. Error must be below 5% for hemolysis-relevant wall shear stress fields.",
      "rationale": "Three systematically refined meshes (4.2M, 12.6M, 37.8M cells, refinement ratio 1.44) were used. Richardson extrapolation applied to hemolysis index, wall shear stress, and velocity magnitude at 5 operating points. GCI values ranged from 1.1% to 3.8% across all QoIs. Fine-grid solution used for all subsequent analyses. Level 4 fully achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions used for validation must be documented with sufficient fidelity to allow faithful reproduction in the simulation, including fluid properties, boundary conditions, and operating point tolerances.",
      "rationale": "FDA benchmark experimental conditions are fully documented in the ASME V&V 40 FDA pump dataset. Fluid properties (viscosity, density) were matched to within 0.5% of experimental values. Boundary conditions (flow rate, rotational speed) were set to match experimental operating points within published uncertainty bands. Level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison between simulation outputs and experimental measurements must use appropriate validation metrics (e.g., MAPE, normalized RMSE) with uncertainty bands on both simulation and experimental data explicitly reported.",
      "rationale": "Quantitative validation metrics computed for velocity fields (PIV comparison), pressure head, and hemolysis index. Mean absolute percentage error for hemolysis index: 11.2% across 5 operating points. Experimental measurement uncertainty (±8% hemolysis index) and simulation uncertainty (Monte Carlo 95th percentile interval ±9%) both reported. Validation metrics satisfy level 4 threshold for MRL 5. Level 4 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The quantities of interest used in validation must be directly relevant to the COU prediction target (absolute hemolysis index), with a documented mapping from validation QoIs to COU QoIs.",
      "rationale": "Primary validation QoI is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH), which is identical to the COU prediction target. Secondary QoIs (wall shear stress distribution, velocity field) are mechanistically linked to hemolysis via the power-law hemolysis model. Relevance mapping documented in technical report TR-QOI-2024-001. Level 4 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must be conducted on a geometry and under operating conditions sufficiently similar to the COU device and conditions to support extrapolation of validation evidence.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump, which is the same geometry as the COU device. Operating conditions span the clinical VAD range (3–6 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM). Validation domain is directly coincident with COU domain. Level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence must be demonstrated for all simulations, with residuals and monitored QoIs shown to reach stable steady-state or periodic values. Round-off error must be assessed.",
      "rationale": "All simulations run to residual convergence below 1e-6 for continuity and momentum. Monitored hemolysis index and pressure head showed less than 0.1% variation over the final 500 iterations. Double-precision arithmetic used throughout; round-off error estimated at machine epsilon level, negligible relative to discretization error. Level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup, execution, and post-processing must follow documented standard operating procedures reviewed by an independent analyst to prevent user-induced errors.",
      "rationale": "Simulation SOPs developed and reviewed by an independent CFD analyst not involved in model development. Checklist-based review of mesh setup, boundary condition assignment, and post-processing scripts completed for all 5 operating points. No use errors identified. Level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The mathematical model form (governing equations, turbulence closure, hemolysis sub-model) must be justified for the COU physics through a documented model selection process that includes comparison of alternative model forms and quantitative assessment of model form uncertainty for the specific flow regime and hemolysis prediction task.",
      "rationale": "The k-omega SST turbulence model was selected based on its established performance in rotating machinery and blood pump applications documented across more than a decade of published literature, including the landmark Hariharan et al. (2011) FDA pump round-robin study and subsequent Morrison (2019) credibility framework work. The power-law hemolysis model (Giersiepen et al. formulation with Heuser-Opitz coefficients) is the most widely used formulation in the field and has been applied in over 40 peer-reviewed publications covering centrifugal and axial blood pumps. Expert panel review conducted by three senior biofluid mechanics researchers with a combined 60 years of experience unanimously endorsed the model form selection as appropriate for VAD hemolysis prediction at the operating conditions of interest. While a formal quantitative comparison of alternative turbulence closures (e.g., realizable k-epsilon, RSM) was not completed for this specific geometry at all five operating points due to computational resource constraints during the assessment window, sensitivity analyses performed at two representative operating points (3 L/min / 2500 RPM and 5 L/min / 3000 RPM) showed hemolysis index differences of less than 15% between SST and realizable k-epsilon, which the expert panel considered acceptable given the broader experimental uncertainty. The hemolysis model form uncertainty was partially characterized through variation of the power-law exponent within published ranges from the literature, yielding a coefficient of variation of approximately 18% on predicted NIH. The assessment team and the credibility review board concluded that the accumulated published evidence, expert consensus, and the partial sensitivity analyses together provide sufficient confidence in the model form for acceptance at this stage, with the understanding that a more comprehensive multi-model comparison would further strengthen the evidence base in future assessments. On balance, the evidence supports proceeding with regulatory submission."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model input parameters must be documented with sources and uncertainty characterization. Sensitivity of QoIs to uncertain inputs must be assessed.",
      "rationale": "All 23 model input parameters documented with sources, nominal values, and uncertainty distributions. Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification (N=2000 samples, Latin hypercube sampling) performed propagating input uncertainties through the hemolysis model. Sobol sensitivity indices computed; top three influential parameters identified as blood viscosity, rotational speed, and power-law exponent. Level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental samples used for validation must be characterized with respect to material properties and manufacturing tolerances, and the number of samples must be sufficient to characterize experimental variability.",
      "rationale": "FDA benchmark dataset uses a single precision-machined acrylic pump geometry with dimensional tolerances within ±0.05 mm of nominal. Blood analog fluid (glycerin-water mixture) characterized for viscosity and density at test temperature. Three independent experimental runs at each operating point used to characterize run-to-run variability (CV < 6% for NIH). Level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Input parameters used in the simulation must be demonstrated to be equivalent to those present in the validation experiments, with documented justification for any differences and their expected impact on QoIs.",
      "rationale": "Simulation input parameters matched to experimental conditions: Reynolds number equivalency confirmed (Re_sim / Re_exp within 1.2% at all operating points), fluid viscosity matched within 0.5%, rotational speed matched within 0.1%. Minor geometric simplifications (shaft seal geometry omitted) assessed via local sensitivity study showing less than 0.3% effect on global hemolysis index. Equivalency documented in TR-EQV-2024-002. Level 3 achieved."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cou2-vad-decision-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-review-board",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility review board has evaluated all 13 ASME V&V 40 credibility factors for COU2 (VAD hemolysis prediction, MRL 5) and concludes that the overall body of evidence is sufficient to accept the CFD model predictions for regulatory submission purposes. Twelve of thirteen factors meet or exceed their required credibility levels, demonstrating a comprehensive and rigorous V&V program. The one factor with a noted shortfall — Model Form — was reviewed in detail by the board. The board acknowledges that a full quantitative multi-model comparison was not completed across all five operating points; however, the extensive published literature base, the expert panel endorsement by three senior biofluid mechanics researchers, and the partial sensitivity analyses at two operating points collectively provide a high degree of informal assurance that the selected model form is appropriate. The 15% maximum difference observed between turbulence model predictions at the sensitivity operating points falls within the combined experimental and simulation uncertainty envelope. The board further notes that the power-law hemolysis model is the de facto standard in the field and that no alternative formulation has demonstrated systematically superior predictive performance for centrifugal pump geometries in peer-reviewed literature. Taking a holistic view of the evidence — including the strong performance on discretization error (GCI < 4%), output comparison (MAPE 11.2% within combined uncertainty bands), and Monte Carlo UQ coverage — the board finds that the model form evidence, while not fully meeting the formal level 3 threshold by the letter of the structured assessment, is compensated by the strength of evidence in the remaining factors and the accumulated external validation literature. The board therefore accepts the submission, with the recommendation that a complete multi-model turbulence sensitivity study be incorporated into the post-market surveillance plan and the next credibility assessment cycle.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
